This will bypass the login and return all records from the users table. However, it is essential to note that this is a simple example and real-world applications may have more complex structures and defenses against SQL injection attacks.

To prevent SQL injection attacks, always sanitize user input using prepared statements or parameterized queries:

```php
$stmt = $conn->prepare("SELECT * FROM users WHERE username=? AND password=?");
$stmt->bind_param("ss", $username, $password);
$stmt->execute();
```

In this example, the prepared statement automatically escapes any special characters in the input, making it safe to use in SQL queries.

